uring the final quarter of year 1 of the program, to generate results, which will inform activities over the remainder of the program.\r\nThe consultant will conduct an analysis of the vocational skills training market system in Kandahar and identify private sector and public actors that have the potential to continue implementing the INVEST model, assuming incentives can be aligned and their capacity can be built over the remaining years of the program. A written report will be submitted that will include: a clear analysis of how the non-formal education market currently functions (services offered, gaps remaining etc.); a clear and realistic vision of how that market can continue to support vulnerable Afghan populations after the program ends; and the design of at least 2 pilot approaches for the program to trial over year 2 with the objective of validating a sustainable handover/ exit strategy. The consultant will also design a capacity assessment tool that can be used to determine how successfully the appropriate actors’ capacity to effectively deliver non-formal education is being built.\r\n','2015-09-01 07:00:00','2015-09-30 07:00:00','','','','','',17284.00,17284.00,NULL,'2015-09-08 07:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'approved',NULL,'','','','For conducting the ‘Sustainability Assessment Study’, the consultant will have primary responsibility for completing the following activities:\r\n1.	Validate assessment methodology with the Mercy Corps program team and technical experts.\r\n2.	Develop/ adapt assessment surveys, evaluation tools and approaches that can provide overall input on program’s sustainability and exit strategy. \r\n3.	Review material provided by Mercy Corps such as project proposal, quarterly reports, market assessment report, logframe, and relevant reports from the comparable INVEST-in-Helmand livelihoods program. \r\n4.	Prepare inception report (maximum 3 pages) detailing the approach, methodology assessment plan and work timetable for review and discussion with Mercy Corps before commencing fieldwork\r\n5.	Document the current market system, key actors, influences and capacity to ensure that all possible options for strengthening this are explored and to ensure that the piloted approaches do not have a negative impact\r\n6.	Conduct desk research. Carry out key informant interviews with identified stakeholders and relevant market actors and focus group discussions with students.  If the security environment inhibits access, the consultant will manage national staff to conduct interviews, providing strong guidance and support.\r\n7.	Outline current market system capability in detail by defining (a) market functions that need to work more effectively if the system is to benefit poor women and men, and (b) specific market players who have the requisite capacity and incentives to perform those functions more effectively.\r\n8.	Determine the current level of sustainability and identify additional steps necessary to ensure a successful program.\r\n9.	Define potential business models (private sector, public sector or in-combination) that can be piloted and scaled in further years of the program.\r\n10.	Prepare sustainability assessment report after debriefing and discussing with Program Manager and other relevant stakeholders; the Advisor will produce a report that does not exceed 20 pages with maximum three pages of executive summary. Further formatting guidelines to be discussed.\r\n11.	Design an assessment tool which can be used to measure the capacity development of the identified actors whom it is planned will deliver services after the program ends, and ensure the program is effectively contributing to their strengthening.\r\n12.	Facilitate a one-day reflection meeting with consortium members including senior management (Managers, Directors and CD). A debrief can be arranged with the donor based on findings.   Facilitate briefing meeting in Kabul with senior Mercy Corps leadership.\r\n','','','2015-12-09 0