 after each training;  Provincial M&E Officer submits to Kabul\"','Number of WUA with one or three plans (count)','',NULL,'',10,NULL,NULL,'2015-11-22 10:16:52','2015-11-22 10:18:36',1,NULL),(662,63,'Prevalence of children 6-23 months receiving a minimum acceptable diet (MAD)','9','Feed the Future Indicator Handbook and FFP indicators ','This indicator measures the proportion of children 6-23 months of age who receive a minimum acceptable diet (MAD), apart from breast milk. The “minimum acceptable diet” indicator measures both the minimum feeding frequency and minimum dietary diversity, as appropriate for various age groups. If a child meets the minimum feeding frequency and minimum dietary diversity for their age group and breastfeeding status, then they are considered to receive a minimum acceptable diet. Tabulation of the indicator requires that data on breastfeeding, dietary diversity, number of semi-solid/solid feeds and number of milk feeds be collected for children 6-23 months the day preceding the survey. The indicator is calculated from the following two fractions: 1. Breastfed children 6-23 months of age in the sample who had at least the minimum dietary diversity and the minimum meal frequency during the previous day ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ------------------------------------ Breastfed children 6-23 months of age in the sample with MAD component data and 2. Non-breastfed children 6-23 months of age who received at least 2 milk feedings and had at least the minimum dietary diversity not including milk feeds and the minimum meal frequency during the previous day ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ------------------------------------ Non-breastfed children 6-23 months of age in the sample with MAD component data Minimum dietary diversity for breastfed children 6-23 months is defined as four or more food groups out of the following 7 food groups (refer to the WHO IYCF operational guidance document cited below): 1. Grains, roots and tubers 2. Legumes and nuts 3. Dairy products (milk, yogurt, cheese) 4. Flesh foods (meat, fish, poultry and liver/organ meats) 5. Eggs 6. Vitamin-A rich fruits and vegetables 7. Other fruits and vegetables Minimum meal frequency for breastfed children is defined as two or more feedings of solid, semi-solid, or soft food for children 6-8 months and three or more feedings of solid, semi-solid or soft food for children 9-23 months. For the MAD indicator, minimum dietary diversity for non breastfed children is defined as four or more food groups out of the following six food groups: 1. Grains, roots and tubers 2. Legumes and nuts 3. Flesh foods (meat, fish, poultry and liver/organ meats) 4. Eggs 5. Vitamin-A rich fruits and vegetables 6. Other fruits and vegetables Minimum meal frequency for non breastfed children is defined as four or more feedings of solid, semi-solid, soft food, or milk feeds for children 6-23 months. For non-breastfed children to receive a minimum adequate diet, at least two of these feedings must be milk feeds. For detailed guidance on how to collect and tabulate this indicator, refer to the WHO document: Indicators for assessing infant and young child feeding practices, Part 2, Measurement, available at http://whqlibdoc.who.int/publications/2010/9789241599290_eng.pdf\r\n','3.3 (6-23 months) and 4.1 (2-5 years)','5.3 (6-23 months) and 5.1 (2-5 years)','Baseline and Endline Reports','Survey','Wahyu Nugroho','This indicator measures the proportion of children 6-23 months of age who receive a minimum acceptable diet (MAD), apart from breast milk. The “minimum acceptable diet” indicator measures both the minimum feeding frequency and minimum dietary diversity, a','Donor and government reports',8,'',7,57,NULL,'2015-11-25 02:32:34','2015-11-25 06:49:34',6,NULL),(663,63,'Increased HDDS','1','Custom','Household food access is defined as the ability to acquire a sufficient quality and quantity of food to meet all household members’ nutritional requirements for productive lives. Household dietary diversity, defined as the number of unique foods consumed by household members over a given period, has been validated to be a useful approach for measuring household food access, particularly when resources for undertaking such measurement are scarce. This guide provides an approach to collecting and measuring household dietary diversity as a proxy measure of household food access.\r\n12 food groups are used. 24 hours recall by the surveyed households.','5.5','7.5','Baseline and Endline Reports','Survey','Wahyu Nugroho','According to FANTA guide http://www.fantaproject.org/sites/default/files/resources/HDDS_v2_Sep06_0.pdf ','Donor and Government Reports',8,'',7,57,NULL,'2015-11-25 02:40:11','2015-11-25 06:47:50',6,NULL),(665,63,'Amount of net additional income change (NAIC)','2','DCED','The amount of net attributable income change (NAIC) indicates the value (in USD) of the total amount of revenue accrued by individuals (e.g. poor farmers, entrepreneurs and employees) relative to a base year, and can be calculated based on the total amount of revenue minus any costs incurred during the reporting year minus the total amount of revenue minus any costs in the base year. Note: convert local currency to USD at the average market foreign exchange rate for the reporting period.&nbsp;\r\nThis is the definition from the DCED: Additional net income (additional sales minus additional costs) accrued to targeted enterprises as a result of the programme per year. In addition, the programme must explain why this income is likely to be sustainable.\r\n','$414.50','$590.30','Baseline and Endline reports','Survey','Wahyu Nugroho','Calculate the total amount of revenue accrued by household relative to a base year. Then compared between baseline and endline','Donor and Government reports',8,'the actual indicator was \"% increase in income based on diversified livelihood options amongst target households\"',7,57,NULL,'2015-11-25 05:44:11','2015-11-25 06:47:12',6,NULL),(666,63,'Average number of livelihoods options','3','','Composite index of main sources of income. Target households are asked to identify their first, second (if any) and third (if any) sources of income. The maximum score is therefore 3.','2','2.8','Baseline and Endline reports','Survey','Wahyu Nugroho','Comparing baseline and endline responses. Respondents are questioned their first, second (if any), and third (if any) main sources of income.','Donor and government reports',8,'This indicator was extracted from the indicator set forth in the proposal to donor of \"% increase in income based on diversified livelihood options amongst target households\"',7,57,NULL,'2015-11-25 05:53:45','2015-11-25 06:46:28',6,NULL),(667,57,'% increase in household level production of inland fish','5','','increase (in kg) of promoted inland fish produced by surveyed baseline and endline respondents. Based on a yearly basis recall of respondents. Respondents are program target direct beneficiary households.','4.6','8.0','Baseline and Endline Reports','Survey','Wahyu Nugroho','Comparing baseline and endline. Household level production is recorded based on year-on-year-basis recall by respondents.','Donor and government reports',8,'',7,57,NULL,'2015-11-25 06:51:47','2015-11-25 07:31:50',6,NULL),(668,63,'# of households with access to nutritious food source','4','','households are program direct beneficiary households. Nutritious food sources included all nutritious foods promoted by the program, including Tilapia fish, Vit-A rich vegetables/fruit, meat and eggs chicken and meat from pigs.','0','1500','Monitoring reports by field staff, endline survey (to triangulate monitoring report)','Household monitoring visit by field officers, endline survey to triangulate monitoring data','Avelina Costa','each ho